# Gentoo Optimizations

# The combination of xs, asm, orc, jit, threads, and kms represents a
# performance-oriented configuration that maximizes hardware utilization and
# system responsiveness. The asm, orc, and jit flags empower software to use
# hand-optimized assembly routines and just-in-time compilation, which
# significantly accelerates tasks like media processing and script execution. By
# including threads and kms, you ensure the system is optimized for multi-core
# parallelism and flicker-free, high-resolution graphics output via the kernel's
# display manager.
*/* xs asm orc jit threads kms

# native-extensions: This flag influences how certain interpreted language
# packages compile performance-sensitive subroutines into native binary code.
*/* native-extensions

# Enable Link Time Optimization (LTO) and Profile-Guided Optimization (PGO).
#
# LTO allows the compiler to perform whole-program optimizations during linking,
# while PGO uses runtime profiling data to guide optimizations during a
# subsequent build. These optimizations can improve performance and reduce
# binary size, but they also increase build time, memory usage, and may expose
# package-specific build issues.
*/* lto pgo

# Unlike the standard glibc malloc, jemalloc significantly reduces memory
# fragmentation and lock contention in heavily multithreaded applications and
# long-running daemons like tmux. Applying this flag universally ensures that
# any software explicitly validated by Gentoo maintainers to support jemalloc
# will use it for better memory efficiency, while safely defaulting to glibc for
# unsupported applications like Emacs to maintain system stability.
*/* jemalloc
